# datalock — Cursor IDE Rules (v1.0.1)
# Renamed from logus-lgpd. .lgs files → .dlk format.

## Import
```python
import datalock as dd
import os
SALT = os.environ["DATALOCK_SALT"]
KEY  = os.environ["DATALOCK_KEY"]
# import logus as lg  ← also works (backward compat)
```

## Quick patterns
read any file:          `df = dd.read("file.csv")`
filter rows:            `df = dd.where(df, uf="SP")`
add column:             `df = dd.add_column(df, taxa=dd.col("renda")*0.27)`
detect PII:             `reports = dd.scan(df)`
mask PII:               `df_safe = dd.mask(df, salt=SALT)`
save encrypted:         `dd.store(df_safe, "out.dlk", key=KEY)`
read encrypted:         `df = dd.read("out.dlk", key=KEY)`
canary tracing:         `dd.store(df, "out.dlk", key=KEY, canary=True)`
mask text:              `dd.mask_text(text, salt=SALT, strategy="semantic")`
scan dir:               `inv = dd.scan_directory("./data/")`
full pipeline:          `result = dd.process("in.csv", salt=SALT, key=KEY, output="out.dlk")`

## Type rules
- dd.mask(pd.DataFrame) → pd.DataFrame
- dd.mask(pl.DataFrame) → pl.DataFrame
- dd.mask(pl.LazyFrame) → pl.LazyFrame
- ALL manipulation functions preserve input type

## Never do
- open("file.dlk") → use dd.read("file.dlk", key=KEY)
- salt == key → must be different
- dd.when(...).when(...) without .otherwise(default)
- hardcode salt/key

## dd.col IS polars.col
dd.col("x").over("group")  dd.col("x").rank("dense")  dd.col("x").str.to_lowercase()

## New in v1.1.5
canary:    dd.store(df, "f.dlk", key=KEY, canary=True)  # transparent inject/strip
semantic:  dd.mask_text(text, salt=SALT, strategy="semantic")  # valid fake CPF/email
scandir:   dd.scan_directory("./data/", min_risk="medium").to_html("report.html")
webhook:   dd.configure(audit_webhook="https://hooks.slack.com/...")
